SIMPLE: starry
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Starry
<hw>Star"ry</hw> <pr>(st⟦aum⟧r"r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Abounding with stars; adorned with stars.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Above the
<xex>starry</xex> sky.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Consisting of, or proceeding from, the stars;
stellar; stellary; <as>as, <ex>starry</ex> light; <ex>starry</ex>
flame</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do not Christians and Heathens, Jews and Gentiles, poets and
philosophers, unite in allowing the <qex>starry</qex> influence?</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Shining like stars; sparkling; <as>as,
<ex>starry</ex> eyes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Arranged in rays like those of a star;
stellate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Starry ray</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European
skate (<spn>Raia radiata</spn>); -- so called from the stellate bases of
the dorsal spines.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Starshine</ent>⟦br⟧
